Dimension: Functional Correctness / Defensive Programming

Location: src/proxy.rs lines 825-828.

Violation:
  let response_bytes = axum::body::to_bytes(body, usize::MAX)
      .await
      .unwrap_or_default();

This reads the ENTIRE upstream response body into memory with no upper bound (usize::MAX = 2^64 bytes on 64-bit). Combined with two concerns:
  (a) A hostile or buggy upstream can push gigabytes of data, causing OOM kill of the proxy process (Denial of Service).
  (b) .unwrap_or_default() silently returns an empty Bytes on failure (network reset, content-length mismatch, decode error). The next line attempts serde_json::from_slice::<Value>(&response_bytes) which will succeed returning Value::Null or fail — either way the VDD engine may operate on truthy-looking empty data. No telemetry distinguishes 'empty body because network failed' from 'empty body because upstream returned {}'.

The VDD adversarial review path REQUIRES the response body, so we cannot skip this read — we need a bounded, error-propagating version.

Mandated Refactor:
  1. Add a config knob `proxy.max_response_bytes: usize` with a sensible default (e.g., 50 * 1024 * 1024 = 50 MiB).
  2. Replace `to_bytes(body, usize::MAX).await.unwrap_or_default()` with:
     match axum::body::to_bytes(body, state.config.proxy.max_response_bytes).await {
         Ok(b) => b,
         Err(e) => {
             warn!(error = %e, "Failed to read upstream response body for VDD; returning raw passthrough");
             return Ok(Response::from_parts(parts, Body::empty()));
         }
     }
  3. If VDD is not enabled, skip the to_bytes read entirely — the current code reads the full body even when vdd_engine.is_none() for token-tracking purposes, but token tracking uses a separate path (convert_response_with_usage already did the read and returned the body). Eliminate the double-buffer.
  4. Add a regression test that feeds a 10MB JSON body and asserts the proxy does not OOM and correctly forwards/reviews it.
